SIMPLE: solecism
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Solecism
<hw>Sol"e*cism</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos><ety>[F.
<ets>sol⟦eacute⟧cisme</ets>, L. <ets>soloecismus</ets>, Gr.
<grk>soloikismo`s</grk>, fr. <grk>soloiki`zein</grk> to speak or write
incorrectly, fr. <grk>so`loikos</grk> speaking incorrectly, from the
corruption of the Attic dialect among the Athenian colonists of
<grk>So`loi</grk> in Cilicia.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An impropriety or
incongruity of language in the combination of words or parts of a
sentence; esp., deviation from the idiom of a language or from the rules
of syntax.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A barbarism may be in one word; a <qex>solecism</qex> must be of
more.</q> <rj><qau>Johnson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any inconsistency, unfitness, absurdity, or
impropriety, as in deeds or manners.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Caesar, by dismissing his guards and retaining his power,
committed a dangerous <qex>solecism</qex> in politics.</q> <rj><qau>C.
Middleton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The idea of having committed the slightest <qex>solecism</qex> in
politeness was agony to him.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Barbarism; impropriety; absurdity.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Solecist</ent>⟦br⟧
